<TITLE> Stocks surge in last trade before Eid </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Sep 25 (bdnews24.com)  Investors, taking a view at the Eid extravaganza, indulged in a buying spree to see stocks rally on Thursday, the last trading day ahead of a nine-day closure thanks to the biggest religious festival. Dhaka Stock Exchange continued to rally for the sixth straight day led by banks and non-bank financial institutions with the turnover continuing to top Tk 4 billion mark. Both institutional and retail investors bought shares on Thursday to make profit in the days to come, according to brokerage house officials. The benchmark DGEN or general index surged 41.36 points or 1.41 percent to end on 2966.81 while the DSI or all share price index finished at 2498.45, up by 34.66 points or 1.40 percent. The blue chip, DSE-20 gained 33.48 points or 1.37 percent to 2466.11. All indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange ended upbeat paced by huge gains in mutual funds, bank and pharmaceuticals shares. The CSCX or selective categories index increased 95.97 points or 1.65 percent to finish at 5892.71. The CASPI or all share price index closed at 8996.68, rising 136.35 points or 1.53 percent while the bourse's blue chip, CSE-30 gained 117.63 points or 1.51 percent to 7862.52. Turnover on the DSE amounted to Tk 4.79 billion through trading of 36,877, 653 shares while the port city bourse witnessed 7,492,323 traded shares with a turnover Tk 648.264 million. Gainers got the better of losers on the DSE by 164 to 45 with eight issues remaining unchanged. Of the traded 139 scrips on the CSE, 109 advanced, 27 declined and three remained unchanged. Atop on the turnover board on the DSE, Beximco Pharma rose 4.67 percent to Tk 136.50. Closely behind it, Summit Power surged to end on Tk 732.25, up by 9.25 pertcent. ACI crept up 0.01 percent to finish at Tk 586.80. Profit-taking, however, led state-owned Titas Gas to slip 1.54 percent to Tk 492.50. Beximco closed at Tk 215.20, up 6.58 percent. The other scrips on the turnover board  Grameen One: Scheme 2, British American Tobacco Bangladesh Company, Union Capital, AIMS 1st Mutual Fund and Lanka Bangla Finance  also rose on buying pressure. bd
